
CHAPTER XIV.

ON the fifth morning, or rather afternoon, a
different step approached--lighter and shorter
--and, this time, the person entered the room.
It was Zillah; donned in her scarlet shawl,
with a black silk bonnet on her head, and a
willow basket swung to her arm.

"Eh, dear! Mrs. Dean," she exclaimed.
"Well I there is a talk about you at Gimmer-
ton. I never thought, but you were sunk in
the Blackhorse marsh, and Missy with you,
till master told me you'd been found, and he'd
